<TEXT>
a federal judge friday ordered georgia to stop 
mandatory drug testing for job applicants until he holds another 
hearing on a lawsuit contending the states new drug testing law is 
unconstitutional 
us district judge robert hall granted a request for a 
temporary restraining order that will allow atlanta lawyer ed 
martin to take a job with the state department of human resources 
without undergoing the test 
the lawsuit opposing the drug testing law which took effect 
july 1 was filed by the georgia association of educators martin 
and two teachers the plaintiffs contend the law violates state job 
applicants constitutional guarantee of privacy 
hall scheduled a hearing on a request for a preliminary 
injunction in the case for aug 16 and 17 and ordered testing of 
all state job applicants halted until then 
michael kramer an attorney for the association argued that the 
new law is too sweeping because it requires testing for all state 
job applicants from teachers to maintenance workers 
under the law anyone refusing to submit to the test or testing 
positive for drugs would be banned from public employment for two 
years and their names would be placed on a state list for an 
indefinite period of time 
association attorneys estimated that 1500 applicants have 
submitted to the drug tests since july 1 
martin found the idea of submitting to the test deeply 
offensive kramer said 
kramer also argued that martin who has been offered a legal job 
in the department of human resources office of regulatory 
services which oversees nursing homes posed no risk to the state 
and should not be required to take the test 
the state passed the new law to make a statement kramer 
said they have no evidence there was any need for this 
acrosstheboard testing 
senior assistant attorney general wayne yancey argued that the 
drug testing law is necessary especially for teachers who are 
the frontlines in trying to educate the students and stop use of 
drugs 
we dont need to have the public work force to be the haven 
for all drug users in the state of georgia yancey said 
martin said he was pleased with the judges ruling i couldnt 
see where they had a right to do that to people he said of state 
legislators who approved the law i had to take a stand 
the other two plaintiffs in the atlanta lawsuit are mary smith 
a sixyear teacher who did not teach during the 19891990 school 
year and wants to return to the classroom and richard schmidt who 
has applied for science teaching jobs 
in granting the temporary restraining order hall said a 1989 
ruling by the us supreme court cannot be used to uphold all parts 
of the georgia law 
in that case the high court approved tests for us customs 
service workers after the government contended drug use by workers 
in sensitive jobs could make them likely targets of bribery or 
blackmail 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

