<DOCNO> AP900720-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the associated press will accelerate 
implementation of its photostream network and installation of the 
ap leaf picture desks aiming at completing the nationwide program 
by the end of 1991 a year earlier than previously announced 
ap president louis d boccardi said thursday the decision to 
attempt to speed up the installation schedule was made in response 
to encouragement from ap member newspapers to put the news agencys 
new photo system in place as soon as possible 
installations of photostream and the ap leaf picture desks will 
start in september in new york the state in which ap will save the 
most money by switching from landline transmission to satellite 
delivery of pictures 
installations will start in october in other northeastern 
states in february 1991 installations will commence 
simultaneously in the three other divisions of the aps domestic 
photo service southeast central and west 
within each region ap teams will be working in more than one 
state at a time but the general order for installations is 
determined by where the greatest savings can be made to help pay 
for the program 
the original timetable had called for a 28month implementation 
schedule but development of hardware and software has proceeded 
at a pace that indicates we should attempt to accomplish this 
enormous task in 16 months boccardi said 
the pace of progress on the installations will depend on several 
factors including site preparation newsroom training and 
decisions by newspaper executives on how they wish to integrate the 
ap leaf picture desk with their production systems boccardi said 
we anticipate that the pace of installations will grow as ap 
and the members gain familiarity with what happens when the leaf 
desk arrives in the newsroom boccardi said ap expects to make 
30 installations by the end of 1990 and the rest through 1991 
he said that the ap would give its members at least a quarterly 
update on the progress of the installation program 
aps us photo network is divided into four regions with 
headquarters bureaus in new york chicago los angeles and 
washington 
in addition to the landline savings the northeastern region is 
the first to begin conversion because of its proximity to aps 
photo and computer headquarters in new york aps technical center 
in new jersey and leaf systems inc in massachusetts leaf systems 
is the company that produces the ap leaf picture desk 
the new york region states in order of installations are new 
york pennsylvania massachusetts rhode island new jersey maine 
vermont new hampshire and connecticut 
installation will begin simultaneously in the other three 
regions in february 1991 in this general order 
chicago region texas ohio indiana kentucky michigan iowa 
nebraska south dakota north dakota minnesota illinois kansas 
missouri wisconsin arkansas oklahoma colorado and wyoming 
los angeles region california nevada oregon washington 
arizona new mexico idaho montana utah alaska and hawaii 
washington dc region louisiana mississippi tennessee 
alabama georgia florida north carolina west virginia virginia 
south carolina maryland and delaware 
additional photo editors will be hired for the four control 
bureaus to edit and transmit pictures from bureaus and newspapers 
in the states under their jurisdiction additional staff also will 
be hired to install the darkrooms and train member newspaper 
staffs technical training for the ap staff has begun and a member 
training program is being designed in addition ap will set up a 
fulltime help desk to assist members with the changeover 
in the present analog photo network black and white pictures 
are transmitted in about nine minutes and color pictures in 30 
minutes when fully implemented photostream will allow digital 
delivery of black and white pictures in one minute each and color 
pictures in three minutes 
the ap also announced that it would use the ap leaf picture desk 
for its internal photo computer system and would discontinue 
development and marketing of the ap vax picture desk which runs on 
digital equipment corp computers 
the ap leaf picture desk exceeds our expectations in power 
speed and functionality said john reid ap vice president and 
director of communications and technology work on new features 
is proceeding rapidly members attending anpatec saw the 
difference and demonstrated an overwhelming preference for the 
leaf 
if an ap member newspaper does not want an ap leaf picture desk 
it may elect to keep its present photo receiver or accept a 
twominute receiver or it may choose to buy an electronic darkroom 
from another company in which case ap will provide that member 
with a rebate of 47 weekly for five years effective on the date 
the member would have received its ap leaf picture desk 
the present photo receiver will be left in place at sites where 
an ap leaf picture desk is installed 
members receiving an ap leaf picture desk and photostream will 
be assessed a surcharge of between 15 and 80 weekly depending on 
circulation 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

