<TEXT>
profits are good for food vendors and gift 
shops at the national parks and the interior department believes 
the government should get a bigger part of the action 
interior secretary manuel lujan said thursday that in future 
contract talks with park concessionaires he will press for higher 
franchise fees he said uncle sam now gets only about 25 percent 
on average of what customers pay 
lujan told a news conference he also intends to seek other 
changes in the park concession system to provide more competition 
several congressional panels are looking into park concessionaire 
profits and the lack of competition for contracts 
two recent investigations by the interior department concluded 
that park concessionaires are reaping millions of dollars in 
profits while paying in some cases less than 1 percent of gross 
receipts to the federal government 
in 1988 gross receipts of concessionaires were reported at more 
than 500 million of which only 125 million went to the national 
park service 
lujan said he had no quarrel with the quality of park 
concessions in general but he said the government should receive 
more money from concession revenues so parks can be improved 
i dont think we will put any concessionaires in a position of 
losing money but the intent is to cut into the excessive 
profits he said he said the park service will push for higher 
franchise fees as contracts come up for renewal over the next few 
years 
lujan declined to say specifically how much more concessionaires 
should pay saying that would tip his hand in upcoming contract 
negotiations but he noted that he considers yellowstone national 
park where the government collects fees of about 22 percent of 
concession receipts as a model 
financial information from concessionaires has been difficult to 
obtain when the recent interior studies included profit figures at 
specific parks the conference of national park concessioners a 
trade group successfully won a court order barring disclosure of 
the information 
environmentalists called lujans announcement a good first step 
for too long now too many concessionaires have been getting a 
sweetheart deal said paul prichard president of the national 
parks and conservation association 
george frampton president of the wilderness society said that 
while lujan is aiming in the right direction congress should pass 
legislation to open the park concession business to competition 
the wilderness society is considering bidding for concession 
rights at some parks including yosemite national park in 
california but frampton said entry into the business is almost 
impossible because of the advantages given an incumbent 
concessionaire 
under the law concessionaires are given preferential contract 
renewal rights that allow them to match any other bid the 
government also has allowed incumbent concessionaires to value 
their capital improvements at parks artificially high making it 
difficult for a competitor to purchase these facilities 
as a result there has been little competition for concession 
rights although business at some of the parks has been highly 
profitable lujan said that of 29 contract bids that have gone out 
only one has attracted competitive interest 
lujan said he hopes to make the bidding system more competitive 
by seeking shorter contracts redefining what should constitute 
preferential rights and adopting new accounting methods when 
setting values for capital improvements by concessionaires 
in addition the national park service plans to use outside 
consultants to analyze concessionaires financial statements 
appraisals and other documents as part of future contract 
negotiations contract talks traditionally have been conducted by 
local park officials who have little financial background 
while some park concessions continue to be run by small 
companies concessionaires at large parks often are subsidiaries of 
major entertainment conglomerates such as mca inc whose park amp 
curry co subsidiary runs concessions at yosemite 
