<TEXT>
salvadoran guerrilla leaders are sticking to 
a stance they had when the last peace talks failed that the 
government must purge the army of rights abusers 
the talks scheduled to resume today in san jose costa rica are 
the third round of unmediated negotiations that started in 
venezuela in may 
rebel leaders say they are preparing for a military offensive 
like one in november their largest ever if the new round of talks 
fails to produce results on the issue of the armed forces 
the leftist farabundo marti national liberation front or fmln 
has fought a series of usbacked governments in a 10yearold 
civil war that has claimed some 72000 lives 
there is a sector of the armed forces that must pay the bill 
for so much oppression imposed on the counry guerrilla commander 
schafik handal the chief rebel negotiator said in an interview 
with the associated press at the rebels mexico city office 
this issue of the role of the military was a major sticking 
point in the last round of talks held in mexico in june between the 
rebels and the conservative government of president alfredo 
cristiani 
salvadoran defense minister gen humberto larios said the army 
will handle the hiring and firing in its ranks 
we do not reject the idea of purifying our institution the 
armed forces like any other insitution is subject to evolution to 
improvement larios said in a recent interview but he said we 
are purifying ourselves 
since 1979 troops and death squads linked to them have executed 
about 30000 people suspected of leftist sympathies international 
human rights groups say no officer has been tried or found guilty 
for such crimes 
the us congress the financial underwriter of the salvadoran 
governments war effort plans to tie military aid for 1991 to 
progress made in peace talks and to prosecution of army officers 
responsible for a november massacre of six jesuit priests 
the war could drag on for years if the military is not 
restructured sen christopher dodd dconn said this week adding 
that about 50 highranking army men should be eliminated 
fifty seems to us a low number said handal top guerrilla 
leaders have suggested that 200 officers should be dropped from the 
ranks 
handal said the armys efforts at selfpurification have been so 
ineffectual that rebel leaders are proposing abolishment of the 
institution in a demilitarization process that would also mean 
the disappearance of the guerrilla fighters 
if larios maintains that the army is being constantly 
purified and nevertheless it continues to play the role of 
repressor then its obvious that purification is not enough to 
clean it up it should be abolished flatout which is our 
conclusion handal said 
the costa rican army was abolished in 1949 costa rica is the 
only country in central america that can claim a stable democracy 
throughout recent decades 
the rebels proposes a police force under civilian command to 
maintain law and order after demilitarization the military is dead 
set against the idea and has gotten cristianis backing 
the continued existence of the armed forces is not a subject 
of discussion the president said after last months fiveday 
round of negotiations 
