<TEXT>
a strict lowfat vegetarian diet can reverse 
damage caused by heart disease according to the findings of an 
american study published in the weekly british medical magazine the 
lancet 
the lifestyle heart trial was conducted on 41 heart disease 
patients by the preventive medicine research institute in 
sausalito calif 
the study found that 82 percent of the heart disease patients 
who adopted such a diet quit smoking and attended 
stressmanagement classes reversed their coronary artery blockages 
what were finding is that heart disease may be completely 
preventable for most people if they are willing to make changes in 
their lifestyle the studys coordinator dr dean ornish said 
in a telephone interview 
the patients all from the san francisco area were recruited 
from pacific presbyterian medical center and from moffitt hospital 
at the university of california at san francisco for the study 
published in lancets july 21 issue 
the 41 aged 3575 were randomly divided into two groups 
the experimental group comprised 22 of the 41 the 22 followed a 
lowfat vegetarian diet took regular exercise attended stress 
management classes and did not smoke eighteen of the 22 or 82 
percent of the group showed an overall reversal in coronary artery 
blockages the study found 
the other 19 among the 41 were assigned to a control group which 
followed the standard program recommended for people suffering from 
coronary artery disease a diet of 30 percent fat moderate 
excercise and no smoking 
ten of the 19 53 percent of the control group experienced a 
worsening of their artery blockages the study found 
this finding suggests that conventional recommendations dont 
go far enough for many people ornish said the guidelines may 
be enough to prevent heart disease but not to reverse it 
the lowfat vegetarian diet included fruits vegetables grains 
and beans the report said 
the only animal products allowed were egg whites and a cup a day 
of nonfat milk or yogurt cholesterol intake was limited to five 
milligrams a day and caffeine was eliminated alcohol was limited 
to two units a day although drinking was not encouraged 
the study took place over a year ornish said followup testing 
will continue for four years to see whether blockages continue to 
reverse 
</TEXT>
