a report blaming newfoundlands roman catholic 
church for failing to stop priests who were sexually abusing boys 
has led archbishop alphonsus penney of st johns to offer his 
resignation to pope john paul ii 
penney made a public apology to the victims and their families 
on wednesday after the scathing report accused him of ignoring and 
then denying claims that boys in newfoundland an island province 
off the east coast of canada had been sexually abused by priests 
for more than a decade 
penney 65 said he accepted full responsibility for failing to 
deal with the scandal which first became public in 1987 five men 
including priests and former priests have been convicted on 
sexual abuse charges in the past three years several others are 
awaiting trial 
for 2 years penney refused calls to step down while more than 
20 of his priests and lay members of the newfoundland catholic 
community were charged with or convicted of sexually abusing boys 
the report written by a commission set up by the archbishop a year 
ago said church officials showed little compassion for the victims 
and aligned themselves with the accused 
we are sorry for the times you were not believed were not 
supported or were ostracized in any way in our community penney 
told a catholic audience in st johns for every word and action 
which may have deepened your pain we are profoundly sorry 
the commission said the church adopted a policy of minimal 
response to the scandal even though it was receiving complaints 
about some sexually deviant priests from parishioners police 
officers social workers and other priests that response the 
report said was woefully inadequate and may have been 
psychologically damaging to all concerned 
the boys it said were the victims of men they had been brought 
up to trust men who abused their position of priestly status and 
