<TEXT>
federal and state environmental officials 
announced an agreement today intended to clear the way for the 
cleanup of dioxincontaminated times beach which has been an 
untouched ghost town since 1983 
morris kay regional director of the federal environmental 
protection agency announced the settlement with syntex 
agribusiness inc a palo alto califbased chemical and animal 
health company at a news conference 
todays agreement calls for syntex to incinerate the 
dioxincontaminated soil from times beach and 27 other sites in 
eastern missouri syntex will design and build the incinerator at 
times beach and then tear it down and remove it when the cleanup 
is complete 
times beach about 20 miles southwest of st louis made 
headlines seven years ago when health officials discovered that 
dioxin in waste oil had been sprayed on the towns streets 
the federal government bought out the town 801 homes and 
businesses in 1983 and began trying to figure out how to clean up 
the contaminated streets 
syntex which was not the producer of the dioxin became 
involved in the settlement because it leased a plant owned by one 
of its subsidiaries to a company that produced the dioxin as a 
byproduct in making a disinfectant 
under federal environmental laws syntex is considered a 
responsible party 
we very pleased with the agreement and we believe the 
agreement addresses the local peoples concern kay said were 
not going to allow anything thats unsafe 
the epa has said the entire cleanup of times beach and other 
missouri sites will cost about 118 million and could take up to 10 
years syntex estimates it will take seven years 
the company declined to say how much it expects to spend on the 
cleanup 
we have accepted this settlement because it allows us to use 
