at least 25 states have some kind of family or 
medical leave program according to the national womens legal 
defense fund 
connecticut maine and wisconsin have family and medical leave 
legislation similar to the law signed friday by district of 
columbia mayor marion barry but the definition of family is more 
limited 
new jersey has a familyleave only legislation while minnesota 
oregon rhode island and washington state have parental leave laws 
kentucky has an adoption leave law only 
ten other states california hawaii iowa kansas louisiana 
massachusetts montana new hampshire tennessee and vermont and 
puerto rico have pregnancy disability leave laws in which women are 
permitted time off only for the time they are physically unable to 
work because of pregnancy or recovery 
florida north carolina north dakota oklahoma pennsylvania 
and west virginia have a variation of family or pregnancy 
disability leave for state employees only 
illinois has passed a medical leave bill similar to the 
districts but it only provides six weeks of leave for every two 
years 
missouri passed a pregnancy leave law but it was vetoed by the 
governor 
the fund said its tally was as of january 
