<TEXT>
associated press writerequals 
washington ap the senate on friday voted down a proposal to 
allow farmers to grow additional amounts of grain before being 
subjected to government management controls 
the amendment to the 1990 farm bill was offered by sen rudy 
boschwitz rminn who said the acreage reduction program in the 
legislation hurts the ability of us farmers to compete in the 
world market 
but supporters of the acreage reduction plan prevailed in their 
arguments that it was needed to control the size of surpluses and 
stabilize prices the amendment was defeated 5037 
boschwitz said the program requires farmers to idle some of the 
most fertile land in the country 
we have foregone production and in the process given the 
markets to the europeans said boschwitz 
sen bob kerrey dneb argued that the export enhancement 
program was designed to get those markets back and could be used 
more effectively by the bush administration 
kerrey said huge grain surpluses are expensive for the 
government 
one of things were trying to do is balance the taxpayer 
desire to keep costs down and producers need for stability he 
said 
the boschwitz amendment was the second major attack on the bill 
designed by the senate agriculture committee to set farm policy for 
the next five years 
the first came thursday in the 6630 defeat of an amendment 
offered by sen harry reid dnev that would have eliminated 
subsidies to farmers with gross sales over 500000 a year 
an agriculture committee source who spoke on condition of 
anonymity said defeat of the two amendments was a good indication 
that the general provisions of the committees bill would stand 
debate will continue next week with a battle over the sugar 
program expected tuesday sen bill bradley dnj has introduced 
an amendment that would reduce the loan rate on raw sugar from 18 
cents to 16 cents a pound it is supported by the bush 
administration 
the sugar program is one of the most controversial support 
systems in us agriculture policy though it does not require 
direct government payments it controls supply by limiting the 
amount of sugar that can be imported thereby keeping prices high 
candy makers and other sugar users dislike the program because 
they are kept from buying the cheaper worldprice sugar foreign 
policy makers say it works against us objectives in places like 
central america where sugar is so easily grown 
while the taxpayers shell out considerable sums of money for 
military and foreign assistance to the region the sugar program 
blithefully undermines our national security by closing our market 
to one of the few ways these same countries have to earn money 
said bradley 
the house begins debate on its version of the farm bill on 
monday 
