<TEXT>
a senatepassed bill would reimpose 
advertising time limits on childrens television shows and require 
stations to provide some programs just for kids 
the bill sent to the house after a unanimous consent vote late 
thursday would limit commercials to 105 minutes per hour on 
weekends and 12 minutes per hour on weekdays for kids programs on 
both broadcast stations and cable similar restrictions were lifted 
from broadcasters in 1984 
the measure also would 
require the federal communications commission to complete an 
investigation that could affect socalled programlength 
commercials that feature toys 
require broadcasters to provide more educational and 
informational programming for kids 
establish a 10 million public tv endowment for childrens 
educational programs 
broadcasters were able to water down provisions that would have 
required stations in order to gain an fcc license renewal to show 
they had substantially increased airings of programs specifically 
designed for kids educational and informational needs 
the bill would allow the fcc to consider nonbroadcast efforts 
on behalf of kids by stations such as programming guides 
despite the lastminute compromises the bill marks a sharp 
turnaround from reaganera deregulation of childrens tv and 
post1984 fcc policy that childrens needs can be served by the 
broad marketplace including cable tv public television and 
vcrs 
the bill also represented a personal victory for longtime 
advocate peggy charren head of bostonbased action for childrens 
television 
ive only been waiting for this for something like 22 years 
for children to be part of the audience the broadcast licensee is 
obligated by law to serve charren who founded act in 1968 said 
in a telephone interview 
we think this is the first step in getting millions of points 
of educational light into american living rooms without raising the 
deficit im sure that everyone who cares about children will be 
applauding the president when he signs the bill into law she 
said 
a similar bill is pending in the house where quick passage also 
is expected president bush has not indicated whether he would sign 
a childrens tv bill but the justice department last year 
recommended that he veto the bill because it intrudes into program 
content president ronald reagan vetoed a similar measure in 1988 
the national association of broadcasters generally has supported 
the bill but resisted a competing measure by sen tim wirth 
dcolo that would have imposed tighter ad limits required the 
larger amount of educational and informational programs and 
outlawed programlength commercials 
nab maintained that familytype programs such as the cosby 
show or national geographic specials should count towards 
broadcasters obligations to children the house bill allows 
broadcasters to serve the needs of children through their overall 
programming 
nab spokesman walt wurfel said the compromise bill does a lot 
to protect the interests of children but it still recognizes that 
the essential element of broadcasters being able to provide this 
programing is a healthy flow of advertising revenue 
until 1984 the fcc had limited commercials on childrens tv 
programs to 95 minutes per hour weekends and 12 minutes weekdays 
during congressional hearings on the house and senate bills there 
was testimony that the amount of commercial ad time has grown 
dramatically on kids shows since 1984 while the amount of 
informational and educational programs for kids had declined 
sharply 
</TEXT>
