the house on friday overwhelmingly passed a 
bill aimed at helping states meet national education goals set by 
president bush and the governors 
the bill approved 35025 authorizes 1 billion in new federal 
education spending in fiscal 1991 and a total of 53 billion over 
the next five years for education initiatives 
the house also voted overwhelmingly 31559 to adopt an 
amendment requiring suspension of federal student financial aid for 
any student convicted of a drug offense 
rep peter smith rvt also won support for an amendment to 
allow states and the education department to pool resources for 
special projects targeted at specific needs in a district the 
projects could be exempt from a wide range of federal and state 
requirements 
i think it is a major opening major reform initiative to 
encourage schools to reinvent themselves for surefire performance 
for all students said smith noting he had won endorsements from 
the national governors association and the presidents education 
advisory council 
the bill arose from the education summit bush and the nations 
governors held in charlottesville va in september 1989 it 
includes several of the statements of education policy goals 
requested by bush as well as broader democratic plans for spending 
programs 
bushs original version called for an estimated 400 million in 
1991 spending the house version increases authorization for 
remedial assistance to disadvantaged children it would authorize 
280 million for awards to exemplary schools and includes money 
for bushs proposed national science scholars program and programs 
to fight illiteracy 
it authorizes more money for financial assistance to college 
students willing to enter the teaching profession and for 
professional development of teachers 
the senate has passed a more limited version of the bill and 
differences will have to be resolved in a conference committee 
