<TEXT>
costs of a popular farm conservation program 
are expected to be higher and its benefits lower than previously 
estimated an agriculture department report said friday 
a reassessment of the conservation reserve program or crp 
shows federal outlays may be 66 billion to 93 billion over the 
lifetime of the program 1986 through 1999 
meanwhile the report said benefits may be 42 billion to 9 
billion 
the conservation reserve program is a longterm plan designed by 
congress in 1985 to take 40 million to 45 million acres of highly 
erodible cropland from production for 10 years planting it to 
grass and trees 
in return farmers get onetime assistance to plant the 
protective vegetative cover plus annual rental payments averaging 
about 50 per acre 
an earlier assessment had put net benefits of the program 
assuming the full 45 million acres to be retired at 34 billion 
to 11 billion and net federal costs at only 26 billion to 66 
billion 
the reassessment is based on current enrollment of 34 million 
acres and reflects the reduced crops stocks and higher prices 
caused by uneven weather other the past few years the report 
said higher prices lessened the commodity program savings that 
might otherwise have been attributed to the crp 
</TEXT>
