traders buying up statesubsidized goods in the soviet union such 
as televisions jewelry caviar and gasoline 
but many soviets have gone west as well buying clothes and 
other consumer goods not easily available in their country 
at the kremlin meeting of the presidential council and the 
federation council gorbachevs top two advisory groups ryzhkov 
outlined his governments plan for the transfer to a market economy 
beginning in 1991 the tass news agency reported 
the official news agency said the plan includes freedom of 
economic activities and enterprise developing a system of 
protecting citizens from increasing prices and unemployment 
decentralizing property and establishing antimonopoly measures no 
specifics were given 
an economic program presented by ryzhkov in may caused panic 
buying that made empty store shelves even barer a new version of 
the plan was ordered with the first phase of food price increases 
put off until 1991 
ryzhkovs new plan outlined friday is to be presented to the 
soviet parliament when it reconvenes in september 
gorbachev stressed that the transfer to a market economy and the 
drawing up of a new union treaty involving the 15 soviet republics 
were two sides of the same coin according to tass 
the treaty which would ensure increased autonomy of the 
republics would also create a single marketoriented system in 
which all component parts will complement each other tass quoted 
gorbachev as saying 
separatist trends only make even more complicated the situation 
both in the republics and the nation in general gorbachev said 
according to the news agency 
to keep the soviet union from splintering gorbachev in june 
proposed the 15 republics agree on a new looser union of 
sovereign states 
since gorbachev began his reforms in 1985 many soviet republics 
have sought to exercise more and more independence from moscow 
the baltic republics of lithuania latvia and estonia have made 
outright moves toward independence the russian federation the 
ukraine moldavia and uzbekistan have declared their sovereignty 
proclaiming that local laws take precedence over soviet law 
