<TEXT>
the energy department has failed to prove that 
its plutonium processing plant near richland wash can be operated 
safely or that it should even be restarted congressional 
investigators said friday 
the department has failed to show that the plant on the hanford 
nuclear reservation is needed to produce plutonium or to help 
manage radioactive wastes said the report by the general 
accounting office 
the plant is called the purex plant short for plutonium 
extraction it uses chemical methods to separate plutonium for 
nuclear weapons produced by the irradiation of uranium nuclear 
reactor fuel rods it has been shut to improve safety since 
december 1988 
doe has not demonstrated that a need exists for the remaining 
weaponsgrade plutonium that could be extracted and it has not 
fully compared purex with other waste processing alternatives to 
determine whether purex is the best approach the gao said 
does plans for restarting purex are inadequate said the 
report requested nearly a year ago by rep mike synar dokla 
chairman of the house government operations subcommittee on 
environment energy and natural resources 
a more important question is whether purex should be restarted 
at all given the costs to operate purex in combination with the 
costs to prepare a supplemental environmental statement the time 
and costs associated with correcting identified safety and training 
deficiencies the fact that most plutonium for new weapons will 
come from old weapons being retired and scrap on hand at weapons 
plants and the possibility that a better alternative exists to 
dispose of the fuelgrade plutonium in the unprocessed fuel rods 
at hanford 
if a decision is made to continue with plans to restart purex 
we believe that a supplemental environmental impact statement 
should be prepared prior to restart of the plant the gao said 
a spokesman for the energy department said watkins had not seen 
the gao report and would have no immediate comment however 
spokesman tim tomastik said the report makes the assumption that 
doe has made a decision about restarting purex the doe has not 
made a decision at this time with respect to whether or not to 
restart purex 
synar said friday his subcommittee estimates that putting the 
plant in mothballs would save the government more than 750 million 
over the next 15 years 
</TEXT>
