<TEXT>
sen dave durenberger should be denounced for 
abusing his office and misusing public funds even though 
emotional and traumatic events impaired his judgment a report 
released friday recommended 
the senate ethics committees report explained the panels 
recommendation announced wednesday that the minnesota republican 
be denounced on the senate floor by a vote of his colleagues 
the committee found that durenberger knowingly violated senate 
rules and federal statutes in a book deal in transactions 
involving the minneapolis condominium he partly owned by failing 
to report expense reimbursements and by accepting free limousine 
rides in violation of gift limits 
the sixmember panel also recommended that durenberger make 
restitution of up to 122780 29050 to the senate for improper 
reimbursements for his condominium and 93730 to charity less 
state and federal taxes already paid for exceeding limits on 
speaking fees the charity figure is about 1000 less than the 
amount announced wednesday 
durenberger has admitted violating senate rules but said he 
never intend to do so he contended also that he always followed 
the advice of his personal lawyers 
the 12year veteran senator also said his judgment was 
influenced by tragedies in his life the death of his first wife 
and the killing in vietnam of his current wifes first husband 
the committee finds that sen durenberger did encounter severe 
emotional strain from events in his personal life the report 
said 
it found that the severe emotional and traumatic events 
impaired his judgment the committee finds that these factors do 
not excuse the senators conduct 
the report said durenberger generated 248300 in speaking fees 
that he classified as promotions for his two books but the 
appearances actually were normal honoraria speeches subject to 
income limits 
durenberger during a great many of these speeches did not 
mention the books he supposedly was promoting when he did 
mention them his only reference was extremely brief or was 
belittling of the books contents the committee found 
while durenberger contended the federal election commission 
approved his book promotion speeches the committee concluded the 
senator misled the agency 
durenberger did not tell the fec he would be making book 
promotion speeches that were strikingly similar to honoraria 
appearances subject to earnings limits and he did not say that his 
promotion appearances would result from invitations to deliver 
traditional honoraria speeches 
the committee found that durenberger placed his minneapolis 
condominium in a partnership as a means of permitting him to 
claim senate reimbursements 
durenberger took his name out of the partnership and as a 
result the senators ownership interest was concealed from the 
senate according to the report 
when his lawyer cautioned durenberger that he could not find a 
legal basis for the reimbursements under the partnership the 
senator failed to take any action and only asked the senate for 
advice after news articles surfaced on the condominium in 1989 
durenberger also arranged a purported sale of the residence 
in 1987 to a business operated by a personal friend and former 
campaign manager 
the friend admitted that he would not have bought the unit but 
for durenbergers agreement to rent it this was an arrangement 
which both parties understood would be financed at least in part 
through senate reimbursements the report said 
durenbergers attorney jim hamilton filed a brief with the 
committee that called the recommended punishment too strong and 
said a strong reprimand would be more fair 
hamilton called the book deal a goodfaith venture and the 
condominium transactions legitimate real estate deals they were 
not shams he said 
