<TEXT>
federal and state environmental officials 
friday announced an agreement intended to pave the way for cleanup 
of the dioxincontaminated ghost town of times beach after seven 
years of study and negotiations 
morris kay regional director of the us environmental 
protection agency announced at a news conference that a cleanup 
agreement had been reached with syntex agribusiness inc a 
chemical and animal health company 
the settlement is subject to a 30day public comment period and 
then approval by us district judge john f nangle but both kay 
and syntex spokesman ray forrester said preliminary work could 
begin within days of the judges decision 
under the settlement syntex will build and later demolish an 
incinerator to burn the tons of dioxintainted soil from times 
beach and 27 other sites in eastern missouri contaminated in the 
1970s when waste oil containing dioxin was sprayed on roads to keep 
dust down 
syntex based in palo alto calif did not produce the dioxin 
but the government considers syntex a responsible party because the 
dioxin was produced by a tenant in a verona plant owned by a 
company syntex later acquired 
i think this agreement is a good compromise forrester said 
it allows the problem to be solved and allows the money to be 
spent on the solution rather than litigation 
the company declined to say how much it expects to spend on the 
cleanup but kay said syntex would do at least half of work the epa 
has estimated would cost 200 million 
under the agreeement syntex must pay the government 10 million 
over five years to cover part of the cost of prosecuting the case 
in return all federal and state lawsuits against the company will 
be dismissed 
we believe that this is a safe effective permanent solution 
to this dioxin contamination and we certainly look forward to the 
day when we can say this cleanup is finished said missouri 
department of natural resources spokeswoman anita randolph 
times beach about 20 miles southwest of st louis has been 
deserted since 1983 when the federal government bought up all 801 
homes and businesses and moved the people out 
guards patrol its fenced perimeter to keep vandals out of 
dilapidated buildings now taken over by weeds and wild animals 
announcement of the settlement brought angry words from 
opponents of the incinerator plan who criticized the secrecy of 
the negotiations and who believe the incinerator will be unsafe and 
will become a permanent fixture 
we will have created the central hazardous waste site of the 
united states if this goes through said state rep jim murphy 
who with several other opponents showed up at the news conference 
a recently passed state law limits an incinerator permit to five 
years 
the epas kay who said the agreement called for the cleanup to 
be completed in five to seven years said all concerns had been met 
we are very pleased with the agreement and we believe the 
agreement addresses the local peoples concerns kay said 
were not going to allow anything thats unsafe 
he said the epa would continue to pursue other potentially 
responsible parties 
dioxin an unwanted byproduct in the manufacture of chemicals 
like disinfectant is suspected of causing disorders of the nervous 
system liver kidneys and bladder it has been found to cause 
cancer in laboratory animals 
the epa says the incinerator would roast the contaminated soil 
so the dioxin molecules break up into carbon oxygen chlorine and 
hydrogen 
the treated soil would no longer be hazardous and would be 
buried in a landfill on site the area would then be safe again for 
habitation although federal flood plain regulations enacted since 
times beach was founded would prohibit building houses there 
randolph said 
as part of the cleanup agreement syntex will demolish all 
buildings on the site and restore it for public use possibly as a 
park or walking trails 
</TEXT>
