canadian indian chiefs on friday called 
for police to withdraw from barricades where they are locked in an 
armed standoff with mohawks who claim land there as ancestral 
territory 
the indians from across canada made the call at the end of a 
threeday conference at the kahnawake reserve south of montreal 
they called the conference to seek solutions for the crisis that 
has left one police officer dead prompted indians from around the 
nation to rally and touched off an antiindian backlash 
at the end of their meeting the indian leaders issued a 
resolution calling for provincial police to pull away from the 
barricades at oka a town 18 miles west of montreal 
the indians are trying to block a plan by municipal officials to 
build a golf course addition on the disputed land 
at fridays conference the indian leaders also asked prime 
minister brian mulroney to reconvene parliament immediately to deal 
with the national crisis 
mohawk chief joe norton said both police and indians should 
withdraw from barricades in oka and from a bridge between montreal 
and its southern suburbs where a sympathy blockade has been set up 
by other indians the bridge blockage has set off angry protests by 
local residents who have burned indians in effigy and made 
antiindian slurs 
norton also said the mohawks at the blockades must be assured of 
amnesty for a settlement to be reached 
however quebec provincial premier robert bourassa has already 
said officials will not agree to amnesty for indians involved in a 
shootout at oka on july 11 a provincial police officer was killed 
but it is not clear if he was killed by gunfire from indians or 
fellow officers 
tom siddon the federal indian affairs minister added friday 
a federal minister cannot set aside the rule of law and deal with 
an element which is using weapons and raising blockades on public 
thoroughfares to achieve their ends 
indians have been manning their barricade at oka for four months 
on thursday federal officials said they would try to acquire 
the disputed land to block the golf course but only if indians 
agree to lay down their arms 
