the national endowment for the arts has agreed 
to let artists also funded by the rockefeller foundation sign a 
modified version of its controversial antiobscenity pledge both 
parties said friday 
joint grantees can add wording to the current nea pledge that 
they will comply with its provisions to the extent that such 
terms and conditions and the requirement to accept them are 
lawful under the constitution and the laws of the united states 
the rockefeller foundation opposes the nea pledge which 
requires grantees to promise not to create obscene works 
in a letter to recipients released friday the foundation said 
it believed the pledges were unconstitutional unfair and 
dangerous to artists and that they limit the range of art 
produced 
the modified language provided a measure of protection for 
artists funded by both agencies it said 
the foundation first disclosed the agreement in a 
friendofthecourt brief filed late wednesday on behalf of the new 
school for social research which sued the nea and refused to sign 
the antiobscenity pledge to get a grant 
the nea confirmed the agreement on friday a spokesman said it 
agreed to the modified language late last month 
because of the comingling of private and public money the 
endowment agreed to a modification of the guidelines said 
spokesman josh dare 
only artists and organizations receiving money from the nea and 
the foundation would be eligible to sign the revised agreement he 
said 
we arent including it for any others dare said its a 
unique funding situation so it turns into a unique compliance 
situation 
the endowment decided earlier this month to use the definition 
of obscenity established in 1973 by the supreme court rather than 
broader language adopted by congress last year dare said 
the antiobscenity language included in the endowments fiscal 
1990 appropriation forbids the nea to fund work that might be 
deemed obscene including but not limited to depictions of 
sadomasochism homoeroticism the sexual exploitation of children 
or individuals engaged in sex acts which when taken as a whole do 
not have serious literary artistic political or scientific 
value 
