<TEXT>
in his 34 years on the supreme court justice 
william j brennan has left his mark in majority opinions that 
helped shaped the law and in dissents that offered tributes to 
individual liberties 
here is a sampling 
in 1957 brennan wrote for the court as it first attempted to 
define obscenity and ruled that obscenity is not constitutionally 
protected he said material is obscene if to the average person 
applying contemporary community standards the dominant theme of 
the material taken as a whole appeals to prurient interest 
in 1962 the court established its oneperson onevote standard 
of equal representation brennan said judges have authority to 
strike down stateapproved legislative district lines the right 
asserted is within the reach of judicial protection under the 
fourteenth amendment he said 
in 1964 the court granted constitutional protection to the news 
media when it is sued for libel brennan wrote the 
constitutional guarantees require we think a federal rule that 
prohibits a public official from recovering damages for a 
defamatory falsehood relating to his official conduct unless he 
proves that the statement was made with actual malice that is 
with knowledge that it was false or with reckless disregard of 
whether it was false or not 
when the court ruled against prison inmates in a littlenoted 
case during the 198687 term brennan wrote in dissent 
prisoners are persons whom most of us would rather not think 
about it is easy to think of prisoners as members of a 
separate netherworld nothing can change the fact however that 
the society these prisoners inhabit is our own when prisoners 
emerge from the shadows to press a constitutional claim they 
speak the language of a charter upon whicch all of us rely to hold 
official power accountable 
when the court ruled that a former soldier who unknowingly 
ingested lsd in secret chemical warfare experiments could not sue 
due the government brennan dissented and said 
the subject of experimentation who has not volunteered is 
treated as an object a samplesoldiers ought not to be asked to 
defend a constitution indifferent to their essential human 
dignity 
