<TEXT>
its a summer school like no other 
students immerse themselves in the works of duke bird and 
miles the dean of faculty once cavorted with cab swung with 
count and bebopped with dizzy 
since 1988 the skidmore summer jazz institute has brought six 
renowned jazz artists and professors to skidmore college to teach 
and play that most of american of music 
no more than 40 musicians ranging in age from 14 to 50something 
pay 1000 each to spend two weeks eating sleeping playing and 
talking jazz with such prominent figures as milt the judge 
hinton considered the elder statesmen of jazz bassists 
hes jazz history walking around here said buddy baker 
another faculty member youre getting it from the guy who lived 
it 
the skidmore summer jazz institute held this year from june 25 
through july 6 is unique because it places such importance on the 
history of jazz and not on the hot new young players baker 
said 
on the institutes fourth day music filters through the walls 
of the janet kinghorn bernhard theater where 36 students divided 
into five groups rehearse in separate rooms 
in one studio a teenager with shaggy blond hair slides his 
fingers up and down a standup bass while his combo of high school 
students works through a tune he wears black pants and a black 
tshirt decorated with white skulls an earring protrudes from one 
nostril 
nearby the judge listens intently then passes down his 
sentence 
ok lets try it again says hinton a bouncy 80yearold 
who brings six decades of jazz experience to skidmore 
tshirts sneakers and shorts are the uniform of the day two 
teenagers in hintons morning class wear their baseball caps 
backward hinton keeping with the casual theme wears blue slacks 
white polo shirt sneakers maroon chintz jacket and golf cap 
he nods toward the blond bassist a very avantgarde dude 
who gave up his electric guitar for the acoustic bass the tune 
ends and hinton is quick to praise 
thats much better mike much better he says 
another bass player steps in this one a tall skinny teen in a 
new york mets tshirt as the boys long fingers pluck out a 
throaty bass line hinton nods his head in satisfaction 
hes really going to make it he says 
hinton knows about making it 
the son of a chicago music teacher he gave up the violin for 
the bass after the introduction of talking motion pictures in 1929 
put him and many other musicians playing in silent movie theaters 
out of work 
a string is a string so i traded a small string for a big 
string hinton said 
in 1935 he signed on with cab calloways band and stayed with 
the flamboyant bandleader until the early 1950s cab calloway 
borrowed me for a while he borrowed me until he could get to new 
york and get a good bass player and i stayed in his band for 16 
years 
afterward came stints with count basie and louis armstrong 
along the way he accompanied everyone from duke ellington and paul 
mccartney to billie holliday and aretha franklin he uses his 
experiences along with some of the tens of thousands of 
photographs he snapped over the years to teach younger generations 
the joys of jazz 
the idea for the institute came from don mccormack dean of 
special programs at skidmore mccormack envisioned a program that 
would allow budding jazz musicians to play with and learn from some 
of the best in the business he took his idea to jerry zaffuts 
then a jazz instructor at skidmore now director of the institute 
zaffuts put together an allstar faculty that could handle a 
classroom as well as a c note except for vince dimartino who 
could not attend last year the faculty has been the same since the 
institute began three years ago 
in addition to hinton the faculty includes ed shaughnessy 
drummer don menza a grammynominated saxophonist dick katz a 
pianist record producer and jazz historian baker a former 
trombonist with the stan kenton and woody herman bands now a 
professor the university of north colorado and dimartino a 
trumpet player who also teaches trumpet and jazz at the university 
of kentucky 
guest artists such as pianist barry harris and bassist rufus 
reid give master classes 
the facultys impressive resumes arent lost on the students 
its like having einstein prove his theory to you while youre 
sitting there said joel mott a 19yearold trumpet player from 
oklahoma city 
most of the applications come from high school and college 
students although this years group included a dentist engineer 
state trooper and quite a few music teachers 
each applicant must submit an audition tape and each undergoes a 
live audition once they arrive at skidmore the students then are 
formed into bands based on their ability their stay is highlighted 
by the two free concerts they perform at the bernhard theater 
in the morning the faculty works with the bands in rehearsals 
later students get oneonone lessons with the faculty member 
specializing in their instrument 
everybody has a really good attitude about trying to give a 
lot to the kids nobody just puts in their time shaughnessy said 
good jazz musicians dont always make good jazz teachers said 
shaughnessy who has performed more than 600 lectureclinics at 
high schools and colleges across the nation 
jazz clubs used to be the training ground for aspiring 
musicians but except for such jazz hotspots as new york and new 
orleans jazz clubs are few and far between 
i really got my education in those clubs i listened to all 
the greatest drummers i watched them for hours said 
shaughnessy who as a teenager in the 1950s frequented the famed 
jazz clubs that lined new york citys 52nd street 
the problem today is finding serious jazz musicians with whom to 
play many of the students said the institute gives them that 
opportunity 
often the advice shaughnessy and the others offer cant be 
found in a text book 
i was telling a quitar player dont try to play so many 
notes when you improvise play more spare shaughnessy said 
he says to me afterward you know thats just what i needed 
thats a bit of street advice 
teaching also takes place in the classroom in katzs history of 
jazz class students delve into its origins and changes listening 
to classic recordings of such greats as earl hines armstrong and 
miles davis hinton also conducts a class a kind of eyewitness 
account of the golden age of jazz peppered with names such as 
calloway armstrong and basie 
those people seem fictitious until you talk to milt said 
mott 
but the faculty does more than teach they perform three times 
during the two weeks once at the newport jazz festival in saratoga 
springs and twice for free at skidmore where its standingroom 
only for the groups electrifying concerts 
for hinton the institute is more than an opportunity to bring 
the jazz club to the jazz student its our responsibility to be 
sure to give them something something that they can leave here 
with 
