<TEXT>
they fled the suffocating world of hanoi to 
pursue their love of music and now two young vietnamese violinists 
are delighting hong kong with the strains of mozart while the 
colony decides whether to send them back 
nguyen sam thi 26 and her 19yearold brother nguyen khac 
uyen gave their first local public recital in early july 16 
months after a harrowing sea journey to this british colony to 
escape their communist homeland 
i dont think my performance was great i was a bit nervous 
thi said after playing a mozart violin sonata before an 
appreciative lunchtime audience at the academy for performing arts 
reviews from arts officials were much more positive theyve 
got good technical background and good music instincts said the 
academys director john hosier 
they are both highly talented musicians with great 
potential said angus watson head of music at the academy 
both believe the vietnamese refugees would be accepted by any 
topnotch conservatory 
but musicianship is not all that the siblings have on their 
minds these days since they are among the 44000 boat people who 
have landed in hong kong after june 1988 they must prove a 
wellfounded fear of persecution back home or face repatriation as 
illegal immigrants 
immigration officials interviewed the two musicians last month 
a decision on whether they will be allowed to resettle in the west 
has yet to be made 
im not too sure about my future a softspoken uyen said 
during a recent interview at the academy i just keep playing my 
violin and i believe music would lead me somewhere 
according to the nguyens who spoke in english it was their 
love for music and the repeated attempts by vietnamese authorities 
to interfere in their artistic development that forced them to flee 
the country 
both have received musical training since early childhood first 
from their father who they said was the chief violinist with the 
vietnamese symphony orchestra and then at the hanoi conservatory 
thi said she was handpicked by a team of soviet music experts in 
1981 and sent to moscow for music studies before being suddenly 
summoned back in 1985 with no explanation uyen said the vietnamese 
authorities nixed numerous offers for him to study in moscow and 
rejected an invitation for him to perform in poland 
eventually they said their parents decided the children had to 
escape vietnam if they were to pursue a career in music 
having paid an agent gold worth more than 1000 thi uyen and 
their mother boarded a 63foot fishing junk that set sail from the 
northern vietnamese port of bai chay in march 1989 with 29 people 
aboard the father stayed behind and has since been fired because 
of the escape his children said 
the group made occasional stops along the chinese coast to take 
on food supplies and for repairs after about 20 days the boat 
reached hong kongs shores 
it may seem silly to other people that i took along my violin 
during the dangerous journey to hong kong but the instrument is my 
most valuable property uyen said 
thi stressed that they intended to continue practicing as soon 
as they reached the territory music has become part of us 
wherever we go whatever situation were in we continue to play 
at first the youths practiced daily at a laundry hut in a 
detention center in rural hong kong but the official in charge of 
the camp quickly appreciated their talent and a battle followed to 
provide thi and uyen with proper musical training 
they have since been granted special permission to live with a 
local german woman and her american husband during the week to 
practice at the academy on weekends they are sent back behind the 
imposing fences of the high island detention center where they 
live in cramped bungalows with thousands of other boat people 
the two violinists say they would gladly go to any country 
willing to offer them refuge 
uyen dreams of becoming a soloist and composer while his 
sisters goal is to play with an orchestra 
let us wait and see we need to practice but we are hopeful 
all the time thi said 
