<TEXT>
if you harbor any doubts that things happen much 
faster than they used to in the world of finance consider the 
recent rise of the dow jones industrial average to the 3000 level 
the familiar gauge of trends in stock market prices was more 
than 100 years old before it surpassed 1500 for the first time on 
dec 11 1985 
the next 1500 points took less than five years thanks to the 
bull market still raging on wall street 
but as impressive as that performance may look it is partly the 
result of a sort of optical illusion created by the math used to 
calculate the average 
the average that appears today in news headlines and 
computerized market reporting systems is a far more complicated 
entity than anything charles henry dow must have had in mind when 
he set out in 1884 to construct a yardstick for measuring the ups 
and downs of stocks 
dow cofounder of dow jones amp co and the first editor of the 
wall street journal picked 11 stocks he deemed representative 
befitting the makeup of the american economy in those days nine of 
his choices were railroads 
by simply adding up the most recent prices of those stocks and 
then dividing by 11 he could figure and publish a market 
average 
in 1896 dow devised an average of industrial stocks separate 
from the railroads with 12 components it was expanded to 20 in 
1916 and 30 in 1928 
as the dow evolved it also had to change its membership 
roster at intervals to keep up with changes in the american 
business scene 
early component stocks such as pacific mail steamship central 
leather and standard rope amp twine yielded in time to the likes of 
american telephone amp telegraph international business machines 
exxon and other of todays corporate giants 
amid all this activity a continuous average could not be 
calculated without making adjustments in the formula 
so the number used as the averages divisor was changed not 
only every time the number of stocks was increased or one was 
substituted for another but also whenever a stock split occurred 
instead of 30 the divisor shrank by stages to about 10 in 1949 
less than two in 1969 and on downward to about 05 today 
in a straight average a rise of 1 each in the price of all the 
component stocks would produce a onepoint increase with todays 
divisor by contrast gains of 1 apiece in the components would 
raise the average about 60 points 
that has given rise to complaints from some observers that the 
average overstates the volatility of todays stock market 
other critics say no sample of 30 stocks can accurately 
represent what happens to investors in more than 1600 issues 
traded on the new york stock exchange and many thousands more 
bought and sold in the various other us markets 
when professional investors compare the results they achieve 
against a market measure they seldom use the dow but refer 
instead to a broader alternative like standard amp poors 500stock 
composite index 
still in news reports and conversations at all levels of the 
economy the industrial average continues to fill the role for 
which it was created as a shorthand symbol of the market 
it stands wrote victor j hillery in a 1986 book on the dows 
history as the most widely recognized measure of the stock 
markets gyrations 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

