<TEXT>
a new satellitetransmitted information 
system is beaming the names of buyers and sellers to farmers with 
too many green peppers or too little sweet corn 
the pilot program by the illinois farm bureau is seen as one 
possible solution to the eternal problem of balancing supply and 
demand in perishable produce as well as possibly boosting profits 
sometimes we have too much and sometimes we dont have 
enough said ron friend who raises cantaloupe and watermelon 
near havana in westcentral illinois along the illinois river i 
remember one day in 1973 it came out exactly right 
fruit and vegetable growers scramble to find wholesale buyers 
when they harvest more fresh commodities than they can sell at 
their roadside markets or to regular customers and they search for 
other farmers with extra produce when their own harvests are short 
the growers seem to be very excited about the system said 
don naylor a specialist in fruit and vegetable marketing who 
manages the new project for the farm bureau were trying to 
bring farmers together who might be separated by hundreds of 
miles 
the farm bureau already had the foundation of the new service 
its farmdayta system for delivering weather market information and 
agricultural news to about 5000 illinois grain producers 
farms receive the data via satellite dish and read it on a 
computer screen twentyfive fruit and vegetable growers were added 
to the system this summer to see if it could help them buy and sell 
produce 
those farmers call a tollfree number to list their names 
locations telephone numbers and crops they wish to buy or sell 
they then must contact buyers or sellers and agree on terms 
we dont raise our own fruit and at times there are local 
shortages said don zeldenrust who grows vegetables and sells 
produce at his chicago heights roadside market 
we might have to go to michigan missouri or arkansas when 
there are guys in southern illinois who have what we need said 
zeldenrust it doesnt make sense to ship the fruit a long way 
its better for them and better for us 
the buyerseller information along with prices being paid at 
chicagos south water street wholesale produce market is 
transmitted to subscribers who pay 100 for six months service 
during the pilot stage of the project 
im using it to keep uptodate on the market said carl 
weissert who grows vegetables near fairview heights in the 
metropolitan area east of st louis 
he said when the system is fully operational the speed at which 
the information is available should be a big plus to farmers 
you wont find out next week what was available said 
weissert 
growers say a limited amount of information now is on the 
system but they hope more farmers will sign up and that it will 
help all of them increase their profits 
right now you just cant find sweet corn anywhere said 
dennis harms who raises and sells fruits and vegetables in mchenry 
county northwest of the metropolitan chicago area 
if this system works we can help each other cut out the 
middleman lower our prices and compete with the big chain stores 
theyre killing us 
</TEXT>
