<TEXT>
president bushs savings and loan bailout fund 
will be nearly out of money if officials reach their goal of 
closing or selling 77 institutions by sept 30 a federal agency 
says 
figures provided thursday by the resolution trust corp 
oversight board indicate that unless congress authorizes more 
borrowing regulators could have as little as 73 billion in 
borrowing authority left when the new federal fiscal year begins 
oct 1 
the bottom line is it would cause us to very 
significantly reduce the pace of resolutions said peter monroe 
president of the oversight board 
congress last year allocated 50 billion to cover sampl losses and 
the oversight board estimates that after the 77 resolutions are 
finished 37 billion of that will have been used however the 
agency will hit a cash crunch before the 50 billion is exhausted 
because of legal caps on its shortterm borrowing 
in addition to the 73 billion the agency could spend any 
money it can get by selling repossessed real estate and sour loans 
inherited from previous sampl bailouts he said 
if congress doesnt provide more money before adjourning for the 
november elections the government will be forced to slow the pace 
of the bailout or dramatically increase the pace of asset sales 
monroe said 
his comments combined with the new figures are the clearest 
indication yet from the administration about the urgency of 
providing additional bailout funds 
in appearances before congressional panels in may and june 
treasury secretary nicholas f brady roughly doubled the 
administrations august 1989 estimate of the bailout cost from 50 
billion to between 90 billion and 130 billion he had said 
additional money would be needed by the end of december or early 
next year 
monroes figures indicate that at the current pace the bailout 
will run out of money soon after sept 30 
so far the trust corporation has resolved the cases of 210 
sampls leaving roughly 250 insolvent thrifts open and under 
government control at least an additional 250 institutions still 
under private ownership are expected to fail 
were twosevenths of the way through monroe said 
because money is scarce officials will concentrate this quarter 
on closing the sampls that are losing money the fastest he said 
in any case officials will never go back to the type of 
deals done in 1988 by the nowdismantled federal home loan bank 
board monroe said because the bank board lacked cash to pay off 
depositors it attracted sampl acquirers through guarantees and other 
subsidies extending up to 10 years 
the 1988 transactions are coming under increasing criticism in 
congress because they virtually ensured lucrative returns to sampl 
buyers who made only a small investment 
the oversight board authorized the trust corporation to borrow 
up to 34 billion through the treasury for the 77 resolutions in 
the julyseptember period this working capital borrowing would 
be repaid as the government sells sampl assets 
in other developments thursday 
angry northeastern and midwestern house members said they were 
introducing a bill to force states with a disproportionate share of 
troubled thrifts such as texas and california to pay a bigger 
portion of bailout costs if a state declines to pay its 
statechartered thrifts no longer would be eligible for federal 
deposit insurance 
other legislation sponsored by rep joe kennedy dmass would 
force wealthy americans to pay more of the cost his bill would 
raise 100 billion over five years by imposing new income taxes on 
individuals earning more than 100000 a year and corporations 
earning more than 75000 a year it also would eliminate a 
provision that forgives inheritance taxes on capital gains at death 
the justice department said it had uncovered certain sampl 
cases where thrift institutions had swapped bad loans with each 
other to avoid regulatory scrutiny but spokesman doug tillett said 
the department has no evidence at this time that suggests the 
existence of a largescale conspiracy among thrifts to trade bad 
loans 
in dallas former sunbelt savings association chairman edwin t 
mcbirney iii known as fast eddie pleaded innocent to bank 
fraud charges sunbelt failed in 1988 at an estimated cost to the 
government of 2 billion 
