<TEXT>
national contract negotiations between the united 
auto workers and the nations big three automakers got into full 
swing as talks began today between the union and chrysler corp 
uaw president owen bieber and chrysler motors president robert 
lutz reached across a large table to shake hands and both sides 
then got down to business 
the uaw started negotiations for new threeyear labor agreements 
on wednesday with general motors corp and thursday with ford motor 
co all three current contracts expire sept 14 
at chrysler the union will be dealing with the automaker in the 
worst financial shape of the big three 
since oct 1 chrysler has been involved in a 15 billion 
costcutting program designed to boost profits but car and truck 
sales for the automaker were running 13 percent behind 1989s pace 
at midyear while fords sales were off 78 percent and gms were 
down 35 percent 
in may the automaker reported it earned 71 million in the 
first quarter of this year down 80 percent from the same time last 
year in the second quarter analysts expect chrysler to make a 
little more than half of the 341 million it earned during the 
second three months of last year 
in 1989 chrysler made 359 million far less than the 38 
billion ford made and the 42 billion gm earned chryslers 
earnings were too small to kick in profitsharing provisions for 
its hourly workers and consequently bonuses for salaried 
employees 
nonetheless the unions initial demands are expected to be the 
same at chrysler as at gm and ford enhanced job security wage 
and pension improvements and protection of healthcare benefits 
the reaction from chryslers management however is likely to 
be far different from responses at gm and ford 
chrysler vice president anthony st john who heads the 
companys negotiating team has said if current contract provisions 
simply are rolled over for another three years it would boost the 
automakers labor costs by 16 percent 
st john said chrysler cant afford that 
his statements have given rise to theories that the death of 
pattern bargaining in the auto industry may be at hand if 
tradition holds sometime around labor day the uaw will choose one 
company and focus negotiating efforts there 
after an agreement is reached that contract would be used as a 
model for talks at the other companies but st johns gloomy 
outlook for the talks may indicate the no 3 us automaker doesnt 
think it will be able to match contract provisions negotiated 
between the union and ford and gm 
there were no such dire economic predictions from gm or ford 
management after hearing uaw statements earlier this week 
as expected the union said it was outraged at gms closures of 
four assembly plants during the past three years and it criticized 
ford for its extensive use of overtime 
the companies said they were looking for more flexibility in 
work rules schedules and the way plants work forces are 
structured 
the contracts between the union and the big three cover more 
than 450000 workers and nearly as many retirees its the first 
time since 1979 that all of the contracts have expired at the same 
time 
</TEXT>
