<TEXT>
financier alan bond has been making 
money on borrowed money since completing his first land deal in 
1960 at age 22 it appears the bill finally has come due 
thirty years after he took out a loan on five acres of land at 
perth in the first step toward building a multinational empire the 
businessman and yachtsman has offered to quit as chairman of his 
flagship bond corp holdings ltd to appease the companys anxious 
creditors who are owed 6 billion 
the agreement under which bond will step down and relinquish 
control of his vast empire was reached thursday although final 
details must still be worked out the deal could clear the way for 
refinancing arrangements that could ultimately save many of bonds 
businesses 
it has been a long fall for bond known for brash and flamboyant 
dealings in business and elsewhere he financed the australian 
sailing teams stunning triumph over the united states in the 1983 
americas cup race 
only three years ago he bought vincent van goghs irises 
from sothebys for what was a thenrecord 539 million a sale 
that the auction house helped him finance in march he sold the 
painting for an undisclosed amount amid reports he had taken a loss 
bond has never been lacking in confidence after emigrating from 
britain with his father to perth in western australia state he 
quit school at age 14 and took a job with a signpainting company 
convincing the owner to take him on even though he did poorly on a 
spelling test 
when things didnt work out he and his father started a 
competitor nusigns that provided the cash for some of his later 
deals 
according to the biography released this week by journalist paul 
barry the rise and fall of alan bond the financier developed 
a strategy of keeping creditors at bay while buying and selling 
land in rapidly developing perth 
he reportedly was close to bankruptcy in 1962 after stringing 
along nusigns creditors too long but managed to work out an 
arrangement at the last minute the next day he made a large 
purchase at a land auction 
barry wrote that with rising land prices bond often would agree 
to buy a plot promising a small deposit then have it immediately 
revalued at a higher price so he could borrow more money than had 
to be paid to the vendor 
with a flair for picking the best development sites and 
promoting them well he had been successful enough to make his 
first 1 million by 1969 at age 29 
he took advantage of eager bankers peddling expensive credit 
particularly after australias financial deregulation in 1983 and 
a stock market full of hungry investors 
at its peak bond corp holdings included interests in brewing 
media natural resources and property he rode out the 1987 stock 
market crash on the cashgenerating strength of his beer businesses 
that actually may have led to his downfall however as bond 
corp holdings picked up steam and eventually ran up debts now 
estimated at about 6 billion 
rising interest rates and bad business decisions alienated 
bonds bankers and creditors put his australian brewing interests 
into receivership and has forced him to sell assets ranging from a 
hong kong office development to a coal mine 
there is speculation that the final straw for bond may have come 
when he tangled with londonbased financier rw tiny rowland 
he bought 204 percent of rowlands lonrho plc in 1988 in a move 
that appeared to presage a takeover attempt 
he was forced to sell a year later telling australian 
television that he underestimated the venom on tiny rowland 
who waged a campaign focusing on bonds debt 
rowland is quoted in barrys book as saying he decided to 
destroy bond after the australian tried to take his yachts parking 
place on the french riviera 
</TEXT>
