<TEXT>
chrysler corp proposed a 
multiemployer healthcare system friday as it joined the rest of 
the big three automakers in contract negotiations with the united 
auto workers union 
but the proposal drew a cool reception from general motors 
corp which opened negotiations with the uaw on wednesday and 
ford motor co which began contract talks thursday the uaw 
offered no reaction friday 
chrysler vice president anthony st john said at a news 
conference following a ceremonial handshake to open talks that he 
proposes forming a trust to administer healthcare programs for 
employees of several companies including auto suppliers 
negotiators from each of the big three say containing 
healthcare costs is a high priority in the current round of talks 
in 1989 gm said it spent about 3 billion in health care costs 
ford spent about 813 million and chrysler paid 684 million 
st john said under a multiemployer program the size of the 
group covered by the plan could be huge keeping costs down he 
said participating companies could also avoid anticipated higher 
costs in 1993 when new financial accounting standards board 
regulations may take effect 
the new regulations would require companies to set aside money 
for anticipated health costs chrysler figures that would be about 
7 per hour per employee or just under 200 million a year 
chrysler says it currently pays for heath care and pension costs 
on a payasyougo basis 
chrysler in the worst financial shape of the big three is 
expected to report by the end of the month that its secondquarter 
earnings were about half of the 341 million it made during the 
period last year 
wall street analysts have speculated that chrysler will lose 
money in the third quarter because its two minivan plants will be 
shut down for a month each to retool for 1991 models the minivan 
is chryslers most profitable vehicle 
chrysler has acknowledged it expects a substantial 
thirdquarter loss 
gm ford and union negotiators so far have declined to talk 
about proposals which may have been advanced in the earliest stages 
of the talks uaw contracts with each of the big three expire sept 
14 
in addition to the healthcare proposal st john said he 
proposed an employee ownership plan which he declined to detail 
and something he called gain sharing which would reward workers on 
a plantbyplant basis based on the financial performance of that 
factory 
in a separate news conference uaw president owen bieber said 
the union issued the same broad proposals friday as it had at gm 
and ford the two days before those involved the need for more job 
security wage and pension improvements and more time off 
if negotiations proceed as they have in the past the uaw will 
bargain with all three companies until sometime around labor day 
and then select a strike target talks at the other two companies 
would be suspended 
a contract reached at the target then would be taken to the 
other two companies in what is called pattern bargaining 
there has been speculation chrysler may break the pattern 
because of its financial problems st john has said simply rolling 
over the current contract would add 16 percent to the companys 
labor costs 
bieber said friday the union had no intention of giving up its 
pattern bargaining strategy 
abandoning the pattern concept will not solve problems he 
said it will create even more chrysler would gain nothing but 
lose a great deal of morale 
</TEXT>
