of 400 champaign county residents 
farmers are interested in peoples attitudes on using the 
technology thats been put into their hands said dennis vercler 
spokesman for the farm bureau 
vercler said farmers are concerned about food safety and the 
environment and many have changed their farming practices to 
reflect that attitude yet many people are unaware of such changes 
because farmers have not told them he said 
they should acknowledge that peoples concerns are real even 
if they dont feel they are justified by the actual risks 
involved said vercler farmers need to communicate better with 
consumers and deal with their perceptions 
vercler was joined at a news conference at the edge of a corn 
field by champaign county farmers who are working to protect the 
environment a display board showed photographs of their new 
practices 
the farm bureau survey found that 51 percent of the people 
surveyed strongly agree that farmers produce healthy food but that 
just 16 percent strongly think farmers are protecting the 
environment 
farmers though have the most to lose if they are careless with 
pesticides or allow chemicals to pollute water and contaminate 
food said tom wolf who raises grain 
i live here with my family and im concerned about our 
safety said wolf and i dont want the next generation to have 
any problems farming the land 
the champaign county survey was similar to a national poll 
conducted by the american farm bureau federation and released 
earlier this week 
other findings in the champaign county survey 
sixty percent of the people said they were very concerned about 
pesticides in drinking water 
fortynine percent of the respondents said farmers use too 
large a volume of chemicals and 14 percent said they use far too 
much 
twentynine percent said farmers are too easily persuaded by 
chemical companies to use more pesticides and 26 percent said 
farmers favor economics over safety 
thirtyseven percent said they think the trend among farmers is 
to use more chemicals 
actually from 1978 to 1988 farmers cut their use of herbicides 
by 21 percent and insecticides by 60 percent in response to both 
environmental and economic concerns the farm bureau said 
