<TEXT>
a federal judge highly critical of the manville 
trust fund was granted broad powers friday that could ensure his 
ability to overhaul the system for paying asbestos victims 
in an order by the chief judge of federal courts in southern new 
york us district judge jack b weinstein received the power to 
rule on any bankruptcy court appeal involving manville corps 1988 
reorganization or the trust 
the future of the 3 billion trust created as part of 
manvilles court reorganization has been up in the air since it 
disclosed it had run out of money to pay 130000 pending and any 
new claims asbestos lawsuits represent the largest product 
liability litigation in us history 
its essential to get some case management going in these 
problems chief judge charles l brieant said in a telephone 
interview from his office in suburban white plains these cases 
have been pending a long time 
brieant said the bankruptcy case remained before us bankruptcy 
judge burton r lifland but that weinstein now was supervising with 
power to transfer any appeal to his own courtroom 
weinstein last week ordered a plan to be drawn up by aug 6 to 
refinance and restructure the trust he also froze all payments by 
the trust until the plan was ready 
separately thomas d lambros chief judge for us district 
court in cleveland this week consolidated more than 100000 
pending lawsuits nationwide against the manville trust and about 40 
companies that made and distributed asbestos 
lambros on friday clarified his interim order saying it 
preserved current court jurisdictions pending discussions on the 
possibility of achieving a universal resolution through a national 
class action 
lambros scheduled a nov 1 hearing he said judges plaintiffs 
and defense lawyers and claimants would meet before then to try 
and reach a solution 
the order giving weinstein expanded power over the manville 
bankruptcy case and the reorganization of the trust rebuffs 
plaintiffs lawyers who dont want the trusts payment mechanism 
altered weinstein and lambros both have criticized the amount of 
trust money that has gone to lawyers 
one attorney eugene locks of philadelphia filed a motion 
challenging weinsteins authority friday with the 2nd circuit court 
of appeals in manhattan 
another challenge was filed earlier this week in district court 
on behalf of 1100 virginia shipyard workers who already have 
settled with the trust and dont want 60 million in payments 
delayed that motion also seeks to bar restructuring of the trust 
hasnt this manville bankruptcy been consummated if so even 
the bankruptcy judge has no authority to restructure or refinance 
the trust said richard glasser a norfolk va attorney 
representing the workers 
weinstein has called for replacing the trusts current scheme 
processing claims on a firstcome firstserved basis with one that 
takes into account the severity of disease and the financial need 
of victims 
asbestos was widely used for decades in shipbuilding 
construction and other industries for its natural insulation and 
heatresistant properties workers who breathed asbestos fibers 
have contracted lung cancer and other severe and oftenfatal 
diseases 
manville once the nations largest asbestos maker sought 
bankruptcy court protection in 1982 because of thousands of 
lawsuits seeking compensation under its reorganization manville 
is separate from the trust but must contribute regular payments 
starting in 1991 
the trust has paid 974 million to settle more than 22300 cases 
so far at an average of 43000 per claim but is out of cash to pay 
new claims 
manville spokesman don ferguson said the company would cooperate 
with the courts on all issues 
