federal regulators accused four west germans 
and three european entities friday of trading in the securities of 
contel corp with inside information about a pending 6 billion 
merger with gte corp 
the seven were identified in court papers filed in new york one 
week after the original charges were brought against individuals 
or entities whose identities are as yet unknown 
the identities of some defendants remained unknown said the 
securities and exchange commission in washington 
last week the sec said the suspects stood to make more than 1 
million in alleged illegal profits on investments of 205125 
the sec identified the individuals accused of trading on inside 
information as ortwin heider of hofheim west germany hansjurgen 
klisch and hannelore mirbachkrahn both of meerbusch and bodo 
pawlik of ratingen all in west germany 
they were accused of buying call options in contel stock 
onetotwo days before contel and gte announced their merger plan 
a call option is the right to buy 100 shares of a stock or stock 
index at a set price before a certain date 
call options are a way for an investor who thinks a stocks 
price will rise sharply to profit on a smaller investment than it 
would take to buy the stock itself 
the merger was announced on friday july 13 the sec alleged 
that the defendants accounted for over 2800 of 6546 contel call 
options purchased on july 11 and 12 the total trading volume in 
contel call option contracts for the three preceding trading days 
was 329 contracts said the sec 
the call options were purchased through the new york offices of 
dean witter reynolds inc in the name of a dusseldorf bank 
simonbank ag 
neither dean witter not simonbank was accused of any wrongdoing 
the new sec complaint also identified three entities accused of 
violating insider trading laws union investment a dusseldorf 
mutual fund and two companies with offices in switzerland nalasag 
corp in geneva and sigesse sa in lausanne 
